config_subtitle: Based on an automated benchmarking routine
report_multiqc_command: /home/ubuntu/pt/envs/.snakemake/conda/017d0e1a/bin/multiqc -i Assembler Benchmark report --filename REPORT -o . -f -p --tag assembler_benchmark --template assembler_benchmark /home/ubuntu/pt/analysis/summary/ --data-format yaml

ab_methods.abstract: The MinION is a portable DNA sequencer that generates long error-prone reads. As both the hardware and analysis software are updated regularly, the most suitable pipeline for subsequent analyses of a dataset generated with a given combination of hardware and software for a given organism is not always clear. Here we present a benchmark for a selection of de novo assemblers available to MinION users, on a read set of Pseudomonas aeruginosa (NCBI taxID: 287). This benchmark is based on a benchmarking routine, designed to facilitate easy replication on a read set of choice and addition of other de novo assembly pipelines.
ab_methods.authors: S. Nicholls and J. Quick, N. Loman
ab_methods.assembly_quality: Produced assemblies were analyzed and compared on continuity and agreement with the reference genome. Quast (version: 4.6.3) was used to determine a wide array of quality metrics in both quality categories and produce synteny plots. To elucidate any bias in the occurence of certain sequences, 5-mers in the assemblies and the reference genomes were compared using Jellyfish (version: 2.2.10). Finally, results were summarized using MultiQC.
ab_methods.readset_quality: Reads in this dataset were generated on a Minion with FLO-MIN106 flowcell with SQK-LSK109 kit. The reads were basecalled using Guppy v1.8.3. Prior to assembly, the quality of the untreated readset was analysed using NanoPlot (version: 1.19.0) and mapped using the mappy module (version: None) in Python3.
ab_methods.pipelines:
smartdenovo

SMARTdenovo is a long read OLC assembly pipeline that was originally intended to work with PacBio reads, but has been shown to produce assemblies of reasonably high continuity from MinION reads as well.
‌
‌Included tools:
  • smartdenovo (version: 1.0.0)

‌Used command:
smartdenovo.pl -p smartdenovo_assembly {input.fastq} > smartdenovo_assembly.mak
make -f smartdenovo_assembly.mak
if [ -e smartdenovo_assembly.cns ]; then mv smartdenovo_assembly.cns {output}; elif [ -e smartdenovo_assembly.dmo.lay.utg ]; then mv smartdenovo_assembly.dmo.lay.utg {output}; fi

minimap2 miniasm

Minimap2 is a fast all-vs-all mapper of reads that relies on sketches of sequences, composed of minimizers. Miniasm uses the found overlaps to construct an assembly graph. As a consensus step is lacking in this pipeline, post-assembly polishing is often required.
‌
‌Included tools:
  • minimap2 (version: 2.14-r883)
  • miniasm (version: 0.3-r179)

‌Used command:
minimap2 -x ava-ont -t 4 {input.fastq} {input.fastq} | gzip -1 > minimap2.paf.gz
miniasm -f {input.fastq} minimap2.paf.gz > minimap2_miniasm.gfa
grep -Po '(?<=S\t)utg.+\s[ACTG]+' minimap2_miniasm.gfa | awk '{{print ">"$1"\\n"$2}}' | fold > {output}

flye

Flye uses A-Bruijn graphs to assemble long error-prone reads. To do so, it follows arbitrary paths through the assembly graph and constructs new assembly graphs from these paths.
‌
‌Included tools:
  • flye (version: 2.3.6-release)

‌Used command:
flye --nano-raw {input.fastq} --genome-size 6791333 --out-dir . --threads 4
mv scaffolds.fasta {output}

N50.title: N50 (Kbp)
N50.description: N50 is the contig length such that using longer or equal length contigs produces half (50%) of the bases of the assembly (kilo base pairs)

Total length.title: Length (Mbp)
Total length.description: The total number of bases in the assembly (mega base pairs).

# mismatches per 100 kbp.title: Mismatches/100kbp
# mismatches per 100 kbp.description: The number of mismatches per 100 kbp

# indels per 100 kbp.title: Indels/100kbp
# indels per 100 kbp.description: The number of indels per 100 kbp

Genome fraction (%).title: Genome Fraction
Genome fraction (%).description: The total number of aligned bases in the reference, divided by the genome size.
